Class 7

switch - it is another conditional statement similar to if but with some limitations

SWITCH SYNTAX:

switch(variable) {

	case value1:
		code;
		break;
	case value2:
		code;
		break;
	default:
		code;
}

value MUST be same TYPE as variable

True:
1. switch doesnt work with boolean, double, long and float

2. every switch statement can be written using if condition

False:
1. every if condition can be written using switch statement (cant work with logical & realtional (>, >=, <, <=)operators)

String timeOfDay="Morning";
String day="Saturday";

switch(timeOfDay) {

	case "Morning":
		SOPln ("Good Morning");
		break;
	case "Noon":
		SOPln ("Good Afternoon");
		break;
	case "Evening":
		SOPln ("Good Evening");
		break;
	case "Night":
		SOPln ("Good Night");
		break;
	case "Saturday":

	default:
		SOPln ("N/A");
}

Loops in Java - executes same block of code multiple times
				Help to avoid repetative code

	while
	do while
	for
	enahnced for loop/advanced for loop/ for each loop

while loop:

int time =13;

if (time>12){ //conditon is true
	System.out.println("good day"); //code executes 1 time
}

while (time>12){
	System.out.println("good day");
}


WHILE SYNTAX

initialize variable;

while (true){
	code;
	incerement/decrement;
}


String day= "Saturday";

if (day){
	SOPln("My favorite Java class");
}

Do While loop

initilize variable

do {
	code;

}while(true condition);

DO WHILE VS WHILE

while --> first checks condition & then perform action
do while --> first performs action & then checks condition

if condtion is false --> do while will execute code ONCE compare to while loop --> no execution

97% of tim we use while loop compare to do while




